translate ru strings:

    old "Sarah turned back around to face Sigmund."
    new "Sarah turned back around to face Sigmund."

    old "I can't go here."
    new "I can't go here."

    old "I can't go to Gallow's creek...I need to go to Rahayal."
    new "I can't go to Gallow's creek...I need to go to Rahayal."

    old "Sarah watched as Sigmund stormed across the road towards her, getting close up to her face."
    new "Sarah watched as Sigmund stormed across the road towards her, getting close up to her face."

    old "Rahayal?"
    new "Rahayal?"

    old "Have you lost your mind?"
    new "Have you lost your mind?"

    old "Sarah looked into his eyes, they seemed filled with rage."
    new "Sarah looked into his eyes, they seemed filled with rage."

    old "You go up those roads and you'll be dead in a week, and that's if you're lucky."
    new "You go up those roads and you'll be dead in a week, and that's if you're lucky."

    old "If you're unlucky they got fates worse than death."
    new "If you're unlucky they got fates worse than death."

    old "Turn back around, go up the road, find a nice family that will take you in and be safe."
    new "Turn back around, go up the road, find a nice family that will take you in and be safe."

    old "I need to go to Rahayal."
    new "I need to go to Rahayal."

    old "Sigmund sighed, frustrated."
    new "Sigmund sighed, frustrated."

    old "Tell me why you would need to go there?"
    new "Tell me why you would need to go there?"

    old "Sarah struggled to find the right words."
    new "Sarah struggled to find the right words."

    old "I...I can't tell you. I just know that I'm supposed to go there."
    new "I...I can't tell you. I just know that I'm supposed to go there."

    old "Telling him about the voice would surely do her no favors."
    new "Telling him about the voice would surely do her no favors."

    old "Well, you're fucked out of luck then, Sarah."
    new "Well, you're fucked out of luck then, Sarah."

    old "Cause I ain't gonna help you kill yourself."
    new "Cause I ain't gonna help you kill yourself."

    old "She kept meeting his eyes."
    new "She kept meeting his eyes."

    old "Then I'll walk the old road by myself."
    new "Then I'll walk the old road by myself."

    old "Sarah could see anger growing in his face."
    new "Sarah could see anger growing in his face."

    old "She knew she couldn't walk the old road by herself. Just the short trip here had shown her that she wasn't prepared for the dangers of life on the road."
    new "She knew she couldn't walk the old road by herself. Just the short trip here had shown her that she wasn't prepared for the dangers of life on the road."

    old "But she also knew Sigmund cared about what happened to her."
    new "But she also knew Sigmund cared about what happened to her."

    old "This was Sarah's gamble, the only one she had."
    new "This was Sarah's gamble, the only one she had."

    old "If Sigmund cared, he wouldn't let her walk the road alone. Even if that meant bringing her along himself."
    new "If Sigmund cared, he wouldn't let her walk the road alone. Even if that meant bringing her along himself."

    old "Sarah...you don't know what's out there."
    new "Sarah...you don't know what's out there."

    old "Please, stay here."
    new "Please, stay here."

    old "Sarah gathered all the courage she had."
    new "Sarah gathered all the courage she had."

    old "I will go to Rahayal."
    new "I will go to Rahayal."

    old "If I can, I want to travel with you. But if you won't take me, I'll walk myself."
    new "If I can, I want to travel with you. But if you won't take me, I'll walk myself."

    old "Suddenly Sigmund turned around and violently kicked the earth, sending dust clouds up, trailing across the road."
    new "Suddenly Sigmund turned around and violently kicked the earth, sending dust clouds up, trailing across the road."

    old "Laughter suddenly erupted from the cart."
    new "Laughter suddenly erupted from the cart."

    old "It was Sakar, now sitting off the back side of the cart."
    new "It was Sakar, now sitting off the back side of the cart."

    old "You gotta hand it to the girl, she's got a spark about her."
    new "You gotta hand it to the girl, she's got a spark about her."

    old "Not to mention, she got you by the balls Sigmund."
    new "Not to mention, she got you by the balls Sigmund."

    old "Sigmund turned back to the cart."
    new "Sigmund turned back to the cart."

    old "Shut your mouth if you know what's good for you!"
    new "Shut your mouth if you know what's good for you!"

    old "There was enough rage in his voice to make Sakar actually go quiet."
    new "There was enough rage in his voice to make Sakar actually go quiet."

    old "Sigmund turned back to her."
    new "Sigmund turned back to her."

    old "You wanted this, Sarah."
    new "You wanted this, Sarah."

    old "Fine, you can have it."
    new "Fine, you can have it."

    old "You ride with us."
    new "You ride with us."

    old "But know that the only reason I'm doing this is because you might survive, and without us, you'd be dead for sure."
    new "But know that the only reason I'm doing this is because you might survive, and without us, you'd be dead for sure."

    old "Sarah felt a smile creep over her face. She'd gotten what she wanted."
    new "Sarah felt a smile creep over her face. She'd gotten what she wanted."

    old "Thank you. I promise I won't be a burden."
    new "Thank you. I promise I won't be a burden."

    old "You'll be a burden. You'll slow us down. You'll cause untold trouble for us."
    new "You'll be a burden. You'll slow us down. You'll cause untold trouble for us."

    old "But hell if I'm gonna have your blood on my hands."
    new "But hell if I'm gonna have your blood on my hands."

    old "If I die and go to the afterlife, the gods can say Sigmund Falraad was a fucking idiot, but at least he always did the right thing."
    new "If I die and go to the afterlife, the gods can say Sigmund Falraad was a fucking idiot, but at least he always did the right thing."

    old "Sarah watched him march back to the cart."
    new "Sarah watched him march back to the cart."

    old "Well get on the wagon then."
    new "Well get on the wagon then."

    old "We need to make good time."
    new "We need to make good time."

    old "Yes, I'm coming!"
    new "Yes, I'm coming!"

    old "Sarah ran right over."
    new "Sarah ran right over."

    old "As she sat down on the box at the front of the cart, she gripped the sides to hold herself in place as the wagon began to rock."
    new "As she sat down on the box at the front of the cart, she gripped the sides to hold herself in place as the wagon began to rock."

    old "She never spared Gallow's Creek another look."
    new "She never spared Gallow's Creek another look."

    old "It was several hours later when they finally had to stop for the night."
    new "It was several hours later when they finally had to stop for the night."

    old "Sigmund had pulled the wagon off the road and begun to climb down."
    new "Sigmund had pulled the wagon off the road and begun to climb down."

    old "If you're going to be with us on this trip, you're gonna have to pull your weight."
    new "If you're going to be with us on this trip, you're gonna have to pull your weight."

    old "She wasn't expecting any special favors. If she could make herself useful again, she would."
    new "She wasn't expecting any special favors. If she could make herself useful again, she would."

    old "You're on cooking duty till we reach Rahayal, and if you burn anything, you're paying for it."
    new "You're on cooking duty till we reach Rahayal, and if you burn anything, you're paying for it."

    old "And out here on the old road, I don't give a damn what you feel or don't feel like."
    new "And out here on the old road, I don't give a damn what you feel or don't feel like."

    old "When I give you an order, it gets followed. That goes for you, same as it goes for them."
    new "When I give you an order, it gets followed. That goes for you, same as it goes for them."

    old "I promise I'll follow your orders, sir!"
    new "I promise I'll follow your orders, sir!"

    old "Don't start with that sir shit, I ain't your daddy. Just do what I tell you."
    new "Don't start with that sir shit, I ain't your daddy. Just do what I tell you."

    old "Of course...uhh...Sigmund."
    new "Of course...uhh...Sigmund."

    old "You can start by setting up the campsite, put up some logs to sit on, a circle for the fire, get food going."
    new "You can start by setting up the campsite, put up some logs to sit on, a circle for the fire, get food going."

    old "Sarah listened as he handed down the instructions to her."
    new "Sarah listened as he handed down the instructions to her."

    old "Once he was finished, she dutifully took towards her tasks."
    new "Once he was finished, she dutifully took towards her tasks."

    old "Though the work was hard, Sarah found a certain gratitude in doing it."
    new "Though the work was hard, Sarah found a certain gratitude in doing it."

    old "She knew that out of everyone on the cart, she had the least right to be here."
    new "She knew that out of everyone on the cart, she had the least right to be here."

    old "Any chance to prove to them that she could bring value, whatever kind, made her feel somewhat better."
    new "Any chance to prove to them that she could bring value, whatever kind, made her feel somewhat better."

    old "When she had finished preparing the campsite, the others finally joined her."
    new "When she had finished preparing the campsite, the others finally joined her."

    old "Fire?"
    new "Fire?"

    old "Sarah had come to expect that Krip was a man of few words."
    new "Sarah had come to expect that Krip was a man of few words."

    old "No, I...I don't know how to make a camp fire."
    new "No, I...I don't know how to make a camp fire."

    old "She could hear Sakar laugh."
    new "She could hear Sakar laugh."

    old "Don't worry, I can make it."
    new "Don't worry, I can make it."

    old "She watched as Sakar knelt down besides the pile of logs and began working his same ritual."
    new "She watched as Sakar knelt down besides the pile of logs and began working his same ritual."

    old "Before long, a fire had started."
    new "Before long, a fire had started."

    old "You know, if you want to survive out here, knowing how to make a fire is a pretty basic skill."
    new "You know, if you want to survive out here, knowing how to make a fire is a pretty basic skill."

    old "Not a lot of fancy restaurants that will do the cooking for you."
    new "Not a lot of fancy restaurants that will do the cooking for you."

    old "I can teach you how it's done, if you want."
    new "I can teach you how it's done, if you want."

    old "I would love to learn"
    new "I would love to learn"

    old "She knew Sigmund had told her to stay away from him."
    new "She knew Sigmund had told her to stay away from him."

    old "But being able to make a fire would be a valuable skill."
    new "But being able to make a fire would be a valuable skill."

    old "Yes, I'd love to learn. IF you would be willing to teach me."
    new "Yes, I'd love to learn. IF you would be willing to teach me."

    old "Sakar leaned back, away from the fire."
    new "Sakar leaned back, away from the fire."

    old "By the time I'm done with you, you'll be able to do it better than old Sigmund."
    new "By the time I'm done with you, you'll be able to do it better than old Sigmund."

    old "She heard Sigmund only growl."
    new "She heard Sigmund only growl."

    old "I think I'm good"
    new "I think I'm good"

    old "She remembered Sigmund telling her to stay away from him."
    new "She remembered Sigmund telling her to stay away from him."

    old "No, but thank you for the offer."
    new "No, but thank you for the offer."

    old "Fine. Just trying to be friendly."
    new "Fine. Just trying to be friendly."

    old "Sarah saw from the corner of her eyes that Sigmund was nodding approvingly to her."
    new "Sarah saw from the corner of her eyes that Sigmund was nodding approvingly to her."

    old "Everyone gathered around the fire, it's heat a welcome relief."
    new "Everyone gathered around the fire, it's heat a welcome relief."

    old "Sarah finished cooking the second meal she'd ever made in her life, and passed the food around."
    new "Sarah finished cooking the second meal she'd ever made in her life, and passed the food around."

    old "If they didn't like it, they didn't seem to show any signs of it."
    new "If they didn't like it, they didn't seem to show any signs of it."

    old "None of the men seemed to be much for the way of conversation."
    new "None of the men seemed to be much for the way of conversation."

    old "The only sounds were knives and forks, scraping across plates."
    new "The only sounds were knives and forks, scraping across plates."

    old "So far so good, right?"
    new "So far so good, right?"

    old "She watched as Sakar looked up."
    new "She watched as Sakar looked up."

    old "I mean...no trouble so far yet."
    new "I mean...no trouble so far yet."

    old "She watched as a smile crept across his face, before he had to start laughing."
    new "She watched as a smile crept across his face, before he had to start laughing."

    old "Well, obviously."
    new "Well, obviously."

    old "Sarah was annoyed at his curt answer."
    new "Sarah was annoyed at his curt answer."

    old "What does he mean?"
    new "What does he mean?"

    old "She turned her answer towards Sigmund."
    new "She turned her answer towards Sigmund."

    old "He means we ain't got much trouble because we ain't up that far on the old road yet."
    new "He means we ain't got much trouble because we ain't up that far on the old road yet."

    old "This part, so far, it's mostly just the Lethram hinterlands."
    new "This part, so far, it's mostly just the Lethram hinterlands."

    old "It's not safe compared to most of the world, but the city guards will occasionally patrol the roads if they notice too many bandits."
    new "It's not safe compared to most of the world, but the city guards will occasionally patrol the roads if they notice too many bandits."

    old "Sigmund gesturd with his knife, further up the road."
    new "Sigmund gesturd with his knife, further up the road."

    old "Up ahead and we'll be hitting the edge of the Korval forest."
    new "Up ahead and we'll be hitting the edge of the Korval forest."

    old "No guards go past that point."
    new "No guards go past that point."

    old "What's beyond there?"
    new "What's beyond there?"

    old "The forest itself is dense."
    new "The forest itself is dense."

    old "You could bring five armies and you wouldn't have enough men to search every corner of it."
    new "You could bring five armies and you wouldn't have enough men to search every corner of it."

    old "So anybody who doesn't like to be found, likes to live there."
    new "So anybody who doesn't like to be found, likes to live there."

    old "Bandits..."
    new "Bandits..."

    old "Bandits, sure. Other scum."
    new "Bandits, sure. Other scum."

    old "And after? What comes after the Korval forest?"
    new "And after? What comes after the Korval forest?"

    old "Well, after the forest we hit the plains of the bandit kingdoms."
    new "Well, after the forest we hit the plains of the bandit kingdoms."

    old "The bandit kingdoms?"
    new "The bandit kingdoms?"

    old "Sarah had heard them talk about it before, but she had never read about it any book."
    new "Sarah had heard them talk about it before, but she had never read about it any book."

    old "I never read anything about that."
    new "I never read anything about that."

    old "Sakar looked up from his plate."
    new "Sakar looked up from his plate."

    old "So, you can read?"
    new "So, you can read?"

    old "She forgot how casually she sometimes gave away hints of her past."
    new "She forgot how casually she sometimes gave away hints of her past."

    old "Yes, my...my family insisted that I learn."
    new "Yes, my...my family insisted that I learn."

    old "Sigmund leaned forward."
    new "Sigmund leaned forward."

    old "The bandit kingdoms are...well they used to be called the central kingdoms."
    new "The bandit kingdoms are...well they used to be called the central kingdoms."

    old "You ever heard of the Union Kingdoms?"
    new "You ever heard of the Union Kingdoms?"

    old "Sarah nodded. Rosanna was part of the union, so she was more familiar with it than any of them might guess to know."
    new "Sarah nodded. Rosanna was part of the union, so she was more familiar with it than any of them might guess to know."

    old "Well, the central kingdoms used to be like that too."
    new "Well, the central kingdoms used to be like that too."

    old "A collection of smaller kingdoms that managed to keep the other powers out by working together whenever it served them."
    new "A collection of smaller kingdoms that managed to keep the other powers out by working together whenever it served them."

    old "But over time, as the central kingdoms began to fall apart, there was one revolution after the other."
    new "But over time, as the central kingdoms began to fall apart, there was one revolution after the other."

    old "Sometimes it was a rival prince. Sometimes an ambitious general. Hell, sometimes just a peasant revolutionairy that saw a chance."
    new "Sometimes it was a rival prince. Sometimes an ambitious general. Hell, sometimes just a peasant revolutionairy that saw a chance."

    old "Sigmund paused for a moment, as if remembering something."
    new "Sigmund paused for a moment, as if remembering something."

    old "But the only thing they all had in common was that only a few years after they made their move, someone else made a move against them."
    new "But the only thing they all had in common was that only a few years after they made their move, someone else made a move against them."

    old "As the kingdoms grew more and more fragmented, power at the top meant less and less."
    new "As the kingdoms grew more and more fragmented, power at the top meant less and less."

    old "Before long, the leaders of each of the kingdoms were essentially only the rulers of the capital cities."
    new "Before long, the leaders of each of the kingdoms were essentially only the rulers of the capital cities."

    old "Beyond the walls of the capital, the reach of the state dissapeared."
    new "Beyond the walls of the capital, the reach of the state dissapeared."

    old "Without a central authority, the only rule about who was in power, became about how had the strength. How was most merciless."
    new "Without a central authority, the only rule about who was in power, became about how had the strength. How was most merciless."

    old "And when it comes to being merciless, there ain't nobody who was willing to go further than the bandit lords."
    new "And when it comes to being merciless, there ain't nobody who was willing to go further than the bandit lords."

    old "They were the only ones who understood, really understood, that strength was the only power that mattered in this new age."
    new "They were the only ones who understood, really understood, that strength was the only power that mattered in this new age."

    old "Sarah watched as the stabbed a piece of meat on his fork and shoved it into his mouth, eating it almost angrily."
    new "Sarah watched as the stabbed a piece of meat on his fork and shoved it into his mouth, eating it almost angrily."

    old "As the bandit lords terrorized the countryside, the farmers living there began to pack up and flee towards places that still had stability, like Mytrha and Lethram."
    new "As the bandit lords terrorized the countryside, the farmers living there began to pack up and flee towards places that still had stability, like Mytrha and Lethram."

    old "When the farmers left, the food started to run short."
    new "When the farmers left, the food started to run short."

    old "Before long, the cities, even the capital cities, were starving."
    new "Before long, the cities, even the capital cities, were starving."

    old "As the people starved, the central kingdoms were like a tinderbox, waiting for an excuse to go off."
    new "As the people starved, the central kingdoms were like a tinderbox, waiting for an excuse to go off."

    old "When the violence finally began, it was more like a madness than any revolution."
    new "When the violence finally began, it was more like a madness than any revolution."

    old "People ripped others apart, murdered for the smallest of reasons, sometimes no reason at all."
    new "People ripped others apart, murdered for the smallest of reasons, sometimes no reason at all."

    old "A bloodlust seemed to take over, and by the end of it, nothing of the old regimes or histories remained."
    new "A bloodlust seemed to take over, and by the end of it, nothing of the old regimes or histories remained."

    old "Sarah watched as he looked at her."
    new "Sarah watched as he looked at her."

    old "After that, the countries of the central kingdoms were so deprived of people and wealth, that they could no longer sustain themselves."
    new "After that, the countries of the central kingdoms were so deprived of people and wealth, that they could no longer sustain themselves."

    old "Their cities had become empty ghost towns. The countryside was empty too."
    new "Their cities had become empty ghost towns. The countryside was empty too."

    old "With no real economy left, the only way to make money was robbing merchants."
    new "With no real economy left, the only way to make money was robbing merchants."

    old "But the more they robbed merchants, the less merchants took to the old road, deciding to instead travel by sea."
    new "But the more they robbed merchants, the less merchants took to the old road, deciding to instead travel by sea."

    old "And that killed the last of it."
    new "And that killed the last of it."

    old "Ever since, it's been groups of bandits, fighting one another to control scraps of land that few people even care about."
    new "Ever since, it's been groups of bandits, fighting one another to control scraps of land that few people even care about."

    old "At any point, you'll find some new bastard in power somewhere, calling himself whatever fancy title he can come up with, until another drives a dagger into his back."
    new "At any point, you'll find some new bastard in power somewhere, calling himself whatever fancy title he can come up with, until another drives a dagger into his back."

    old "Sarah watched as Sigmund threw a piece of bone into the fire."
    new "Sarah watched as Sigmund threw a piece of bone into the fire."

    old "Now you know what we're heading into."
    new "Now you know what we're heading into."

    old "Never say I didn't warn you, Sarah."
    new "Never say I didn't warn you, Sarah."

    old "Sarah had been quiet for the entire time that Sigmund had spoken."
    new "Sarah had been quiet for the entire time that Sigmund had spoken."

    old "Now she didn't know what to say."
    new "Now she didn't know what to say."

    old "She instead decided to focus back on her meal."
    new "She instead decided to focus back on her meal."

    old "It didn't taste as bad as she had feared."
    new "It didn't taste as bad as she had feared."

    old "As several more hours passed, each had eaten their fill and the night had fully set in."
    new "As several more hours passed, each had eaten their fill and the night had fully set in."

    old "Everyone retreated to their makeshift beds, hoping for an easy night."
    new "Everyone retreated to their makeshift beds, hoping for an easy night."

    old "Sarah laid on her back, looking up at the stars overhead."
    new "Sarah laid on her back, looking up at the stars overhead."

    old "As much as she tried, she wasn't able to get to sleep."
    new "As much as she tried, she wasn't able to get to sleep."

    old "All around her, she could hear the sounds of the others snoring."
    new "All around her, she could hear the sounds of the others snoring."

    old "Slowly, careful not to wake any of the others, Sarah climbed out of her bedroll."
    new "Slowly, careful not to wake any of the others, Sarah climbed out of her bedroll."

    old "Though it was night, the bright moon and a cloudless sky cast a pale light over everything."
    new "Though it was night, the bright moon and a cloudless sky cast a pale light over everything."

    old "Sarah began to walk away from the cart, a little ways down the road."
    new "Sarah began to walk away from the cart, a little ways down the road."

    old "She could hear the harsh gravel crack under her footsteps."
    new "She could hear the harsh gravel crack under her footsteps."

    old "On a normal day, she likely would not have even noticed, but on a lonely night even the smallest sounds seemed to echo."
    new "On a normal day, she likely would not have even noticed, but on a lonely night even the smallest sounds seemed to echo."

    old "As she walked further along the road, Sarah could see the fields of grass, waving from side to side."
    new "As she walked further along the road, Sarah could see the fields of grass, waving from side to side."

    old "Just as they had said, the further they got out from Lethran, the deeper nature grew."
    new "Just as they had said, the further they got out from Lethran, the deeper nature grew."

    old "She had walked for a few minutes down the road."
    new "She had walked for a few minutes down the road."

    old "Here, just over the edge of a small hill, she could look out further ahead."
    new "Here, just over the edge of a small hill, she could look out further ahead."

    old "The moonlight falling on the road ahead made it seem as though it was made out of white marble."
    new "The moonlight falling on the road ahead made it seem as though it was made out of white marble."

    old "She could trace the road all the way until it vanished into the edge of the forest."
    new "She could trace the road all the way until it vanished into the edge of the forest."

    old "A creeping feeling came over her, as though something from inside the forest was looking back at her."
    new "A creeping feeling came over her, as though something from inside the forest was looking back at her."

    old "Sarah shivered and pushed the idea from her mind."
    new "Sarah shivered and pushed the idea from her mind."

    old "Turning back around, she could see the cart, not too far away."
    new "Turning back around, she could see the cart, not too far away."

    old "A gust of wind blew past her and Sarah wrapped her arms around herself, trying to shield herself from the cold."
    new "A gust of wind blew past her and Sarah wrapped her arms around herself, trying to shield herself from the cold."

    old "Ever since she'd gotten out on the road, Sarah realized she'd spend most of her life in the company of others."
    new "Ever since she'd gotten out on the road, Sarah realized she'd spend most of her life in the company of others."

    old "Growing up in Castle Reinmeer, she could not remember any day where she had ever been alone."
    new "Growing up in Castle Reinmeer, she could not remember any day where she had ever been alone."

    old "Traveling to Lethram with Kate, equally, she was constantly in the presence of others."
    new "Traveling to Lethram with Kate, equally, she was constantly in the presence of others."

    old "But here, out on this road, deep in the night...Sarah felt alone."
    new "But here, out on this road, deep in the night...Sarah felt alone."

    old "Sure, there were the others from the cart, but they didn't know her, not really. They simply saw what they thought she was."
    new "Sure, there were the others from the cart, but they didn't know her, not really. They simply saw what they thought she was."

    old "Suddenly, the sound of a twig snapping caused Sarah to spin around."
    new "Suddenly, the sound of a twig snapping caused Sarah to spin around."

    old "In the darkness, off the side of the road, a shade."
    new "In the darkness, off the side of the road, a shade."

    old "It took her eyes a moment longer to recognize it."
    new "It took her eyes a moment longer to recognize it."

    old "Sakar."
    new "Sakar."

    old "He casually waved at her, as though she hadn't just caught him sneaking up on her."
    new "He casually waved at her, as though she hadn't just caught him sneaking up on her."

    old "So casual."
    new "So casual."

    old "Do you think you're funny?"
    new "Do you think you're funny?"

    old "Funny?"
    new "Funny?"

    old "Sneaking up on me all the time."
    new "Sneaking up on me all the time."

    old "He threw his hands up in the air."
    new "He threw his hands up in the air."

    old "What can I say? I have light feet."
    new "What can I say? I have light feet."

    old "Sarah wanted to punch him, but she knew that wasn't a wise idea."
    new "Sarah wanted to punch him, but she knew that wasn't a wise idea."

    old "She'd felt alone before, but now she felt vulnerable."
